# Package Constraints

- 2GP managed packaging only; no unmanaged metadata in production
- Never modify standard object labels inside the package
- Avoid hardcoded record type IDs — use Schema.SObjectType methods
- Custom settings used for subscriber config must be hierarchy type
- Custom metadata types preferred over custom settings for static config
MEM

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#  .claude/rules/
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
cat > .claude/rules/apex-standards.md << 'RULE'
# Apex Standards

- Bulkify all public methods handling collections — design for 200+ records
- No SOQL or DML inside loops — collect and execute outside
- Use `with sharing` by default; document every `without sharing` exception
- Use `WITH USER_MODE` in all SOQL queries accessing platform data
- Prefer bind variables in SOQL — never concatenate user input into queries
- Service layer pattern: separate domain logic from controllers/triggers
- Use TestDataFactory for test data — never `@isTest(SeeAllData=true)`
- One trigger per object, delegate to handler class (Kevin O'Hara pattern)
- Guard all collection access: check `.isEmpty()` before `.get(0)`
- Limit method complexity: max 40 lines per method, extract helpers
RULE

cat > .claude/rules/lwc-standards.md << 'RULE'
# LWC Standards

- Prefer `@wire` for read operations where applicable
- Use `@AuraEnabled(cacheable=true)` for read-heavy Apex endpoints
- Keep JS modules under 200 lines; split complex logic into utility modules
- Every component must have Jest tests; target 80%+ coverage for critical UI
- Follow SLDS design tokens — never hardcode colors, spacing, or fonts
- Use lightning-record-form / lightning-record-edit-form where possible
- All user-facing strings must use custom labels for i18n readiness
- Follow WAI-ARIA accessibility guidelines; test with screen readers
- Use NavigationMixin for navigation — never window.location
- Wire adapters over imperative calls unless mutation is needed
RULE

cat > .claude/rules/security-rules.md << 'RULE'
# Security Rules

## CRUD/FLS Enforcement
- Check `Schema.sObjectType.*.isAccessible()` before SOQL reads
- Check `isCreateable()`, `isUpdateable()`, `isDeletable()` before DML
- Use `WITH USER_MODE` in SOQL as preferred approach (Spring '23+)
- Use `Security.stripInaccessible()` for field-level stripping

## SOQL Injection Prevention
- Always use bind variables: `WHERE Name = :userInput`
- If dynamic SOQL is unavoidable: `String.escapeSingleQuotes()`
- Whitelist-validate field names and sort directions in dynamic queries

## Data Protection
- Never log PII, passwords, keys, or tokens via `System.debug()`
- Never return secrets or credentials in agent/MCP responses
- Store secrets in Named Credentials or Protected Custom Metadata
- No hardcoded URLs, IPs, or credentials in source code

## XSS / CSRF
- In Visualforce: always use `HTMLENCODE()`, `JSENCODE()`, `URLENCODE()`
- In LWC: never use `innerHTML` with user-supplied content
- Custom REST endpoints must validate CSRF tokens

## Hooks and Automation
- Shell hooks must have audited command whitelists
- MCP endpoints must never expose org credentials
RULE

cat > .claude/rules/2gp-packaging.md << 'RULE'
# 2GP Packaging Rules

- Version control is the source of truth — never develop in packaging org
- Package versions are beta until explicitly promoted
- Run `sf package version create --code-coverage` to enforce 75%+ coverage
- Promote only after all tests pass: `sf package version promote`
- Use `--installation-key` for all managed package versions
- Ancestor version must be set correctly for upgrades
- Never remove public/global Apex classes or methods in upgrades
- Test install/upgrade paths in scratch orgs before promoting
- Package dependencies must pin exact versions, not ranges
- Use `sf package version list` to audit version history before release
RULE

cat > .claude/rules/cli-usage.md << 'RULE'
# CLI Usage Rules

- Always use `sf` (unified CLI) — never legacy `sfdx`
- Deploy: `sf project deploy start` (not `force:source:push`)
- Retrieve: `sf project retrieve start` (not `force:source:pull`)
- Test: `sf apex run test --code-coverage --result-format human`
- Scratch org: `sf org create scratch -f config/project-scratch-def.json`
- Auth: `sf org login web --alias <alias>`
- Set default: `sf config set target-org <alias>`
- Package: `sf package version create -p <alias> -w 30 --code-coverage`
- Always pass `--json` when parsing output programmatically
- Use `--wait` flags to avoid polling loops in scripts
RULE

cat > .claude/rules/source-tracking.md << 'RULE'
# Source-Driven Workflow

## Principles
- Version control (Git) is the single source of truth — not any org
- All metadata changes must flow through source control
- No manual changes in production — deploy only via CI/CD or CLI

## Development Flow
1. Create feature branch from main
2. Create scratch org: `sf org create scratch`
3. Push source: `sf project deploy start`
4. Develop in scratch org + local IDE (bidirectional sync)
5. Pull changes: `sf project retrieve start`
6. Run tests locally + in scratch org
7. Commit, push, PR, merge

## Conflict Resolution
- Preview before deploy: `sf project deploy preview`
- Use `.forceignore` to exclude environment-specific metadata
- Resolve merge conflicts in source format, never in org

## .forceignore Essentials
- Exclude profiles unless explicitly managed in package
- Exclude user-specific settings (compactLayouts, listViews)
- Include in git: `.forceignore`, `sfdx-project.json`, `config/`
RULE

